ting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mortimer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mortemer in Seine-Maritime, France, so called from Old French <i>mort(e)</i> ‘dead’ + <i>mer</i> ‘sea’, probably referring to a stagnant pond or drained swamp.","Irish (of Norman origin): the Norman surname in sense 1 above was taken to Ireland from England in the medieval period, where it has also been adopted by bearers of the Gaelic surnames <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> and <b>ÓMuircheartaigh</b>, commonly Anglicized as <b>McMurty</b> and <b>Mortagh</b>. Compare   McMurdo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mortimore","meanings":["English (Devon; of Norman origin): variant of   Mortimer  ."]},{"name":"McMurdo","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muircheartaich</b>, ‘son of Muircheartach’, a personal name meaning ‘sea-ruler’. In Scotland the name was often lenited to give   McCurdy  . Compare   Murdoch   and   Moriarty  . The name was also used to Anglicize <i>Mac Murchaidh</i> (see   McMorrow  )."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Mortimer was born in 1145, in Scotland as the daughter of Robert De Mortimer and wife Robert De Mortimer. She married William de Isaac Malet in 1173, in Fife, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1145–":"1145–Surnud","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1173–1194":"1173–1194","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","before 1145":"enne 1145","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1173":"1173","1194":"1194","Europe":"Europe","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1145–":"1145–Kuollut","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1125–Male":"1125–Kuollut","1173–1194":"1173–1194","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","before 1145":"ennen vuotta 1145","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1173":"1173","1194":"1194","Europe":"Europe","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1145–":"1145–Décédée","1145–Female":"1145–Décédée","1125–Male":"1125–Décédé","1173–1194":"1173–1194","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","before 1145":"avant 1145","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1173":"1173","1194":"1194","Europe":"Europe","Scotland":"Écosse","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Écosse","Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Fife, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Maud de Mortimer est née en 1145, à Écosse, fille de Robert De Mortimer et wife Robert De Mortimer. Elle a épousé William de Isaac Malet en 1173, à Fife, Écosse. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"1145–":"1145–Verstorben","1145–Fema